{
  "query": "What are the documented benefits and harms of adopting reduced tillage systems on European farms?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across 42 individual studies and reviews from Belgium, Denmark, France, Germany, Hungary, Ireland, Lithuania, the Netherlands, Slovakia, Switzerland and the UK, documented benefits of reduced tillage include: increased biomass, species richness or abundance of earthworms; greater abundance of some invertebrates other than earthworms; increased numbers of some weeds and/or weed species; higher Eurasian skylark nest density, earlier laying dates and shorter foraging distances on reduced tillage fields; and greater abundance of some birds (including Eurasian skylark, seed\u2011eating songbirds and gamebirds) in late winter on non\u2011inversion or conservation tillage. A review reported that tillage had negative effects on invertebrate numbers and that no\u2011till systems had more invertebrate bird food resources. A small replicated UK trial found more Farmland Bird Index species on broadcast than on non\u2011inversion tillage fields. Two studies examining long\u2011term effects (10 years) found mixed outcomes for earthworms: one showed higher earthworm biomass under reduced tillage, while another found no difference in earthworm abundance compared to conventional tillage. Documented harms or non\u2011benefits include: negative, no effect, or inconsistent effects on abundance/biomass/species richness of some invertebrates (other than earthworms) and earthworms; no effect or reductions in the number of different plant species found as seeds and in some weed species; no effect on mammal abundance; no effect for some bird species; one study found bird preferences for conservation tillage fields decreased over time; and crop type influenced weed numbers under different tillage regimes. [126]",
  "action_ids": [
    "126"
  ]
}

